The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, May 22, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, May 21: The rate of inflation stood unchanged at the previous weeks figure of 4.2 per cent for the week ended May 8, even as prices of atta, maida, rawa and condiments and spices fell. The point-to-point wholesale price index inflation stood firm, despite the increasing prices of wheat, eggs and some edible oils. The index was at 6.76 per cent in the year-ago period. WPI also stood firm at 181.1 points in the latest reported week with fuel prices remaining firm, despite oil prices touching a 13-year high of over $40 a barrel in the global market. The index was 173.8 points in the year-ago period.																								 Mumbai, May 21: Sermo Montaigu of France will buy out the balance 50 per cent holding in Sermo PM India Ltd (SPMIL) from its joint venture partner, Voltas Ltd, for Rs 5.2 crore, subject to regulatory approvals. The Rs 13-crore paid-up capital of SPMIL is currently held in equal proportion  65 lakh shares of Rs 10 each aggregating Rs 6.5 crore each  by Voltas and Sermo.																								 Ahmedabad/New Delhi, May 21: Buckling under pressure from the Securities and Exchange Board of India, BSE and investors, Sardar Sarovar Narmada Nigam Ltd today postponed the May 28 meeting for seeking bondholders approval for prepaying costly bonds.																								 Calcutta, May 21: The Central Board of Direct Taxes will introduce a new taxpayer scheme named online tax accounting system from June 1. 																								 Chennai, May 21: The new factory of Chennai-based Sundram Fasteners Limited was inaugurated in Haiyan county in China today. This is the companys first overseas venture.
